b'<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>\n\n\n\n<!DOCTYPE workbook_page PUBLIC " -//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Workbook Page MathML 3.8//EN" "http://oli.web.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_workbook_page_mathml_3_8.dtd">\n<workbook_page id="p3_enthalpy_formation" xmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/"\n    xmlns:bib="http://bibtexml.sf.net/" xmlns:pref="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/preferences/"\n    xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:theme="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/presentation/"\n    xmlns:wb="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/activity/workbook/">\n\n\n    <head>\n        <title>Standard Enthalpy of Formation</title>\n        <objref idref="enthalpy"/>\n    </head>\n\n    <body>\n\n        <p>Standard enthalpies of formation provide a convenient means to calculate the enthalpy of\n            reactions. A standard enthalpy of formation, <m:math display="inline">\n                <m:mrow>\n                    <m:mtext>\xce\x94</m:mtext>\n                    <m:msubsup>\n                        <m:mi>H</m:mi>\n                        <m:mi>f</m:mi>\n                        <m:mtext>o</m:mtext>\n                    </m:msubsup>\n                </m:mrow>\n            </m:math>, of a pure substance is the enthalpy change for a reaction in which exactly 1\n            mole of that substance is formed from the elements in their most stable states under\n            standard state conditions. These values are especially useful for computing or\n            predicting enthalpy changes for chemical reactions that are impractical or dangerous to\n            carry out, or for processes for which it is difficult to make measurements. If we have\n            values for the appropriate standard enthalpies of formation, we can determine the\n            enthalpy change for any reaction, which we will practice in the next section on Hess\xe2\x80\x99s\n            law. </p>\n        <p>The standard enthalpy of formation of CO<sub>2</sub>(g) is \xe2\x88\x92393.5 kJ/mol. This is the\n            enthalpy change for the reaction that forms CO<sub>2</sub>(g) from the elements: </p>\n        <formula>$$\\mathrm C(s)\\;\\;+\\;{\\mathrm\n            O}_2(g)\\;\\rightarrow\\;{\\mathrm{CO}}_2(g)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm\\Delta H_\\mathrm\n            f^\\mathrm o=\\;\\mathrm\\Delta H_{298}^\\mathrm o=\\;-393.5\\;\\mathrm{kJ}$$. </formula>\n\n        <p>The reactants are the elements in their \xe2\x80\x9cstandard states\xe2\x80\x9d, which is the most stable form\n            of the element at a pressure of 1 atm and 25 \xc2\xb0C. For the element carbon, the standard\n            state is graphite, because this is the most stable form of carbon under at 1 atm and 25\n            \xc2\xb0C. For oxygen, the standard state is O<sub>2</sub>(g). The product of the formation\n            reaction is one mole of CO<sub>2</sub>, also at 1 atm and 25 \xc2\xb0C. For nitrogen dioxide,\n                NO<sub>2</sub>(g), <m:math display="inline">\n                <m:mrow>\n                    <m:mtext>\xce\x94</m:mtext>\n                    <m:msubsup>\n                        <m:mi>H</m:mi>\n                        <m:mi>f</m:mi>\n                        <m:mi>o</m:mi>\n                    </m:msubsup>\n                    <m:mtext/>\n                </m:mrow>\n            </m:math> is 33.2 kJ/mol. This is the enthalpy change for the reaction:</p>\n        <formula>$$\\frac12{\\mathrm N}_2(g)\\;+\\;{\\mathrm\n            O}_2(g)\\;\\rightarrow\\;{\\mathrm{NO}}_2(g)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm\\Delta H_\\mathrm\n            f^\\mathrm o=\\;\\mathrm\\Delta H_{298}^\\mathrm o=\\;+33.2\\;\\mathrm{kJ}$$ </formula>\n        <p> A reaction equation with 1/2 mole of N<sub>2</sub> and 1 mole of O<sub>2</sub> is\n            correct in this case because the standard enthalpy of formation always refers to 1 mole\n            of product, NO<sub>2</sub>(g). </p>\n        <p>You will find a table of standard enthalpies of formation of many common substances in\n            this <link\n                href="https://cnx.org/contents/havxkyvS@13.1:2gdkQpYU@10/Appendix-G-Standard-Thermodynamic-Properties-for-Selected-Substances"\n                target="new"> Table of Thermodynamic Properties</link>. These values indicate that\n            formation reactions range from highly exothermic (such as \xe2\x88\x922984 kJ/mol for the formation\n            of P<sub>4</sub>O<sub>10</sub>) to strongly endothermic (such as +226.7 kJ/mol for the\n            formation of acetylene, C<sub>2</sub>H<sub>2</sub>). Note that the standard enthalpy of\n            formation of an element in its most stable form is equal to zero.  </p>\n        <example>\n            <p> Ozone, O<sub>3</sub>(g), forms from oxygen, O<sub>2</sub>(g), by an endothermic\n                process. Ultraviolet radiation is the source of the energy that drives this reaction\n                in the upper atmosphere. Assuming that both the reactants and products of the\n                reaction are in their standard states, determine the standard enthalpy of formation,\n                    <m:math display="inline">\n                    <m:mrow>\n                        <m:mtext>\xce\x94</m:mtext>\n                        <m:msubsup>\n                            <m:mi>H</m:mi>\n                            <m:mi>f</m:mi>\n                            <m:mi>o</m:mi>\n                        </m:msubsup>\n                        <m:mtext/>\n                    </m:mrow>\n                </m:math> of ozone from the following information: </p>\n            <formula>$$3\\;O_2(g)\\;\\;\\rightarrow\\;\\;2\\;O_3(g)\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\;\\mathrm\\Delta\n                H_{298}^o=\\;+286\\;kJ\\;$$ </formula>\n            <p>\n                <m:math display="inline">\n                    <m:mrow>\n                        <m:mtext>\xce\x94</m:mtext>\n                        <m:msubsup>\n                            <m:mi>H</m:mi>\n                            <m:mi>f</m:mi>\n                            <m:mi>o</m:mi>\n                        </m:msubsup>\n                        <m:mtext/>\n                    </m:mrow>\n                </m:math> is the enthalpy change for the formation of one mole of a substance in its\n                standard state from the elements in their standard states. Thus, <m:math\n                    display="inline">\n                    <m:mrow>\n                        <m:mtext>\xce\x94</m:mtext>\n                        <m:msubsup>\n                            <m:mi>H</m:mi>\n                            <m:mi>f</m:mi>\n                            <m:mi>o</m:mi>\n                        </m:msubsup>\n                        <m:mtext/>\n                    </m:mrow>\n                </m:math> for O<sub>3</sub>(g) is the enthalpy change for the reaction: </p>\n            <formula><m:math display="block">\n                    <m:mrow>\n                        <m:mfrac>\n                            <m:mn>3</m:mn>\n                            <m:mn>2</m:mn>\n                        </m:mfrac>\n                        <m:mtext/>\n                        <m:msub>\n                            <m:mtext>O</m:mtext>\n                            <m:mtext>2</m:mtext>\n                        </m:msub>\n                        <m:mtext>(</m:mtext>\n                        <m:mi>g</m:mi>\n                        <m:mtext>) </m:mtext>\n                        <m:mo lspace="3px" rspace="3px">&rarr;</m:mo>\n                        <m:mtext/>\n                        <m:msub>\n                            <m:mtext>O</m:mtext>\n                            <m:mn>3</m:mn>\n                        </m:msub>\n                        <m:mtext>(</m:mtext>\n                        <m:mi>g</m:mi>\n                        <m:mtext>) </m:mtext>\n                    </m:mrow>\n                </m:math>\n            </formula>\n            <p> For the formation of 2 mol O<sub>3</sub>(g), <m:math display="inline">\n                    <m:mrow>\n                        <m:mtext>\xce\x94</m:mtext>\n                        <m:msubsup>\n                            <m:mi>H</m:mi>\n                            <m:mn>298</m:mn>\n                            <m:mi>o</m:mi>\n                        </m:msubsup>\n                        <m:mtext/>\n                    </m:mrow>\n                </m:math> = +286 kJ. This ratio,<m:math display="inline">\n                    <m:mrow>\n                        <m:mfenced open="(" close=")">\n                            <m:mfrac>\n                                <m:mtext>286 kJ</m:mtext>\n                                <m:mrow>\n                                    <m:mtext>2 mol</m:mtext>\n                                    <m:msub>\n                                        <m:mtext>O</m:mtext>\n                                        <m:mtext>3</m:mtext>\n                                    </m:msub>\n                                </m:mrow>\n                            </m:mfrac>\n                        </m:mfenced>\n                    </m:mrow>\n                </m:math> , can be used as a conversion factor to find the heat produced when 1 mole\n                of O<sub>3</sub>(g) is formed, which is the enthalpy of formation for\n                O<sub>3</sub>(g): </p>\n            <formula>$$\\require{cancel}\\mathrm\\Delta\n                H^\\circ\\;\\mathrm{for}\\;1\\;\\mathrm{mole}\\;\\mathrm{of}\\;{\\mathrm\n                O}_3(g)\\;\\;=\\;\\;1\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}\\;{\\mathrm\n                O}_3}\\;\\times\\;\\frac{286\\;\\mathrm{kJ}}{2\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}\\;{\\mathrm\n                O}_3}}\\;\\;=\\;\\;143\\mathrm{kJ}$$ </formula>\n            <p>Therefore, <m:math display="inline">\n                    <m:mrow>\n                        <m:mtext>\xce\x94</m:mtext>\n                        <m:msubsup>\n                            <m:mi>H</m:mi>\n                            <m:mi>f</m:mi>\n                            <m:mi>o</m:mi>\n                        </m:msubsup>\n                        <m:mo lspace="0px" rspace="0px">[</m:mo>\n                        <m:msub>\n                            <m:mtext>O</m:mtext>\n                            <m:mtext>3</m:mtext>\n                        </m:msub>\n                        <m:mtext>(</m:mtext>\n                        <m:mi>g</m:mi>\n                        <m:mtext>)</m:mtext>\n                        <m:mo lspace="0px" rspace="0px">]</m:mo> <m:mtext> = +143 kJ/mol.</m:mtext>\n                    </m:mrow>\n                </m:math>\n            </p>\n        </example>\n        <example>\n            <p>Writing Reaction Equations for <m:math display="inline">\n                    <m:mrow>\n                        <m:mtext>\xce\x94</m:mtext>\n                        <m:msubsup>\n                            <m:mi>H</m:mi>\n                            <m:mi>f</m:mi>\n                            <m:mi>o</m:mi>\n                        </m:msubsup>\n                        <m:mo/>\n                    </m:mrow>\n                </m:math>\n            </p>\n            <p>Write the heat of formation reaction equations for:</p>\n            <p>(a) C<sub>2</sub>H<sub>5</sub>OH(l)</p>\n            <p>(b) Ca<sub>3</sub>(PO<sub>4</sub>)<sub>2</sub>(s)</p>\n            <p>Remembering that <m:math display="inline">\n                    <m:mrow>\n                        <m:mtext>\xce\x94</m:mtext>\n                        <m:msubsup>\n                            <m:mi>H</m:mi>\n                            <m:mi>f</m:mi>\n                            <m:mi>o</m:mi>\n                        </m:msubsup>\n                        <m:mo/>\n                    </m:mrow>\n                </m:math> reaction equations correspond to the formation 1 mole of the compound from its\n                constituent elements under standard conditions, we have:</p>\n            <formula><m:math display="block">\n                    <m:mrow>\n                        <m:mtext>(a) 2 C(</m:mtext>\n                        <m:mi>s</m:mi>\n                        <m:mtext>, graphite) + 3</m:mtext>\n                        <m:msub>\n                            <m:mtext>H</m:mtext>\n                            <m:mn>2</m:mn>\n                        </m:msub>\n                        <m:mtext>(</m:mtext>\n                        <m:mi>g</m:mi>\n                        <m:mtext>) +&nbsp; </m:mtext>\n                        <m:mfrac>\n                            <m:mtext>1</m:mtext>\n                            <m:mtext>2</m:mtext>\n                        </m:mfrac>\n                        <m:mtext/>\n                        <m:msub>\n                            <m:mtext>O</m:mtext>\n                            <m:mtext>2</m:mtext>\n                        </m:msub>\n                        <m:mtext>(</m:mtext>\n                        <m:mi>g</m:mi>\n                        <m:mtext>) &nbsp;&nbsp;</m:mtext>\n                        <m:mo lspace="3px" rspace="3px">&rarr;&nbsp;&nbsp;</m:mo>\n                        <m:mtext/>\n                        <m:msub>\n                            <m:mtext>C</m:mtext>\n                            <m:mn>2</m:mn>\n                        </m:msub>\n                        <m:msub>\n                            <m:mtext>H</m:mtext>\n                            <m:mn>5</m:mn>\n                        </m:msub>\n                        <m:mtext>OH(</m:mtext>\n                        <m:mi>l</m:mi>\n                        <m:mtext>)</m:mtext>\n                    </m:mrow>\n                </m:math>\n            </formula>\n            <formula>\n                <m:math display="block">\n                    <m:mrow>\n                        <m:mtext>(b) 3 Ca(</m:mtext>\n                        <m:mi>s</m:mi>\n                        <m:mtext>) + </m:mtext>\n                        <m:mfrac>\n                            <m:mtext>&nbsp;1</m:mtext>\n                            <m:mn>2</m:mn>\n                        </m:mfrac>\n                        <m:mtext/>\n                        <m:msub>\n                            <m:mtext>P</m:mtext>\n                            <m:mn>4</m:mn>\n                        </m:msub>\n                        <m:mtext>(</m:mtext>\n                        <m:mi>s</m:mi>\n                        <m:mtext>) + 4</m:mtext>\n                        <m:msub>\n                            <m:mtext>O</m:mtext>\n                            <m:mn>2</m:mn>\n                        </m:msub>\n                        <m:mtext>(</m:mtext>\n                        <m:mi>g</m:mi>\n                        <m:mtext>) </m:mtext>\n                        <m:mo lspace="3px" rspace="3px">&nbsp;&nbsp;&rarr;&nbsp;&nbsp;</m:mo>\n                        <m:mtext>C</m:mtext>\n                        <m:msub>\n                            <m:mtext>a</m:mtext>\n                            <m:mn>3</m:mn>\n                        </m:msub>\n                        <m:mtext>(P</m:mtext>\n                        <m:msub>\n                            <m:mtext>O</m:mtext>\n                            <m:mn>4</m:mn>\n                        </m:msub>\n                        <m:msub>\n                            <m:mtext>)</m:mtext>\n                            <m:mn>2</m:mn>\n                        </m:msub>\n                        <m:mtext>(</m:mtext>\n                        <m:mi>s</m:mi>\n                        <m:mtext>)</m:mtext>\n                    </m:mrow>\n                </m:math>\n            </formula> \n            <p> Note: The standard state of carbon is graphite, and of phosphorus is \n                    P<sub>4</sub>. The standard state of a substance can be determined from the\n                    <link\n                        href="https://cnx.org/contents/havxkyvS@13.1:2gdkQpYU@10/Appendix-G-Standard-Thermodynamic-Properties-for-Selected-Substances"\n                    target="new"> Table of Standard Thermodynamic Properties</link>. The state of an\n                element whose <m:math display="inline">\n                    <m:mrow>\n                        <m:mtext>\xce\x94</m:mtext>\n                        <m:msubsup>\n                            <m:mi>H</m:mi>\n                            <m:mi>f</m:mi>\n                            <m:mi>o</m:mi>\n                        </m:msubsup>\n                        <m:mo lspace="0px" rspace="0px"/>\n                    </m:mrow>\n                </m:math> is 0 is the standard state for that element. </p>\n        </example>\n        <wb:inline idref="entalpy_form_lbd" purpose="learnbydoing"/>\n        <wb:inline idref="enthalpy_form_digt" purpose="didigetthis"/>\n\n    </body>\n</workbook_page>\n'